(Test format strings edge cases and error handling)

(Empty and single-character strings)
a text called "empty example" is "".
a text called "single example" is "A".
Print "Empty: '{empty example}'".
Print "Single: '{single example}'".

(Large numbers and precision)
a number called "big" is 999999999.
a float called "precise" is 123.456789012345.
Print "Big: {big}".
Print "Big hex: {big:x}".
Print "Precise: {precise:.8}".
Print "Precise short: {precise:.2}".

(Zero and negative values)
a number called "zero_example" is 0.
a number called "negative_example" is -42.
a float called "negative_float_example" is -3.14.
Print "Zero: {zero_example}".
Print "Negative: {negative_example}".
Print "Negative float: {negative_float_example}".
Print "Neg + pos: {negative_example add 100}".
Print "Neg * neg: {negative_example multiply negative_example}".

(Boolean values)
a boolean called "true_example" is true.
a boolean called "false_example" is false.
Print "True: {true_example}".
Print "False: {false_example}".
Print "True as int: {true_example add 0}".
Print "False as int: {false_example add 0}".

(Complex nested expressions)
a number called "x" is 1.
a number called "y" is 2.
a number called "z" is 3.
Print "x + y + z: {x add y add z}".
Print "x * y * z: {x multiply y multiply z}".
Print "(x + y) * z: {x add y multiply z}".
Print "x + (y * z): {x add y multiply z}".
Print "Complex: {z multiply z add x divide y}".
